That's perfect! Here's an example of an Nginx configuration for SSL termination and reverse proxy:

```
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name yourdomain.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem;

    ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
    ssl_ciphers HIGH:!aNULL:!MD5;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:3000; # Replace with your backend's URL
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name yourdomain.com;

    # Redirect HTTP to HTTPS
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
```

In this example, Nginx listens on port 443 for HTTPS traffic and uses your Let's Encrypt certificate for SSL. It also forwards requests to your backend server running on localhost:3000 (you can replace this with the correct backend). The second block redirects all HTTP traffic to HTTPS.

After you save this configuration in your Nginx configuration file (typically located in `/etc/nginx/sites-available/`), test it with `nginx -t` to ensure there are no syntax errors, then reload the service with `sudo systemctl reload nginx`.

