Great question! Managing unauthenticated users is key to creating a seamless user experience. Here's how you can handle such cases:

### 1. Redirect to Login:
The most common approach for unauthenticated users is to redirect them to a login or signup page when they try to access protected parts of your app. Your route guard can handle this:
```javascript
import { auth } from "../firebase";

router.beforeEach((to, from, next) => {
  const requiresAuth = to.matched.some(record => record.meta.requiresAuth);

  if (requiresAuth && !auth.currentUser) {
    next("/login");
  } else {
    next();
  }
});
```
When unauthenticated users attempt to access a protected route, they’ll be redirected to `/login`. You can also enhance this by storing the originally requested route and redirecting back after login:
```javascript
let originalRoute = null;

router.beforeEach((to, from, next) => {
  const requiresAuth = to.matched.some(record => record.meta.requiresAuth);

  if (requiresAuth && !auth.currentUser) {
    originalRoute = to.fullPath;
    next("/login");
  } else {
    next();
  }
});

// After login
router.push(originalRoute || "/dashboard");
```

### 2. Show a Message to Unauthenticated Users:
Instead of redirecting, you could show an error message or a modal explaining why access is restricted. For example:
```vue
<template>
  <v-container>
    <v-alert type="error" v-if="!user">
      Please login to access this page.
    </v-alert>
    <v-btn v-if="!user" @click="redirectToLogin">Go to Login</v-btn>

    <div v-else>
      <!-- Authenticated content goes here -->
    </div>
  </v-container>
</template>

<script>
import { auth } from "../firebase";
export default {
  data() {
    return {
      user: auth.currentUser
    };
  },
  methods: {
    redirectToLogin() {
      this.$router.push("/login");
    }
  },
  created() {
    auth.onAuthStateChanged((user) => {
      this.user = user;
    });
  }
};
</script>
```

### 3. Provide Guest Access (Optional):
For some note-taking apps, you might allow non-registered users to try the app without logging in. You can create a "guest mode" by assigning a temporary UID, storing notes locally or in a Firestore collection for guests. However, encourage users to register to save their work long-term.

### 4. Combine Both Approaches:
You can initially show an explanatory message, and include links to sign up/log in. Afterward, redirect users once they interact with login/signup buttons. For example:
```vue
<template>
  <v-container>
    <!-- Show message -->
    <div v-if="!auth.currentUser">
      <v-alert type="info">
        Please log in to create and view your notes.
      </v-alert>
      <v-btn @click="redirectToLogin">Login</v-btn>
      <v-btn @click="redirectToSignup">Signup</v-btn>
    </div>

    <!-- Authenticated content -->
    <div v-else>
      <v-card>
        <v-card-title>Welcome, {{ auth.currentUser.email }}</v-card-title>
      </v-card>
    </div>
  </v-container>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  methods: {
    redirectToLogin() {
      this.$router.push("/login");
    },
    redirectToSignup() {
      this.$router.push("/signup");
    }
  }
};
</script>
```

Using this approach ensures your app is secure while providing clear guidance to unauthenticated users. Let me know if you'd like to explore additional user flow ideas!

