Sure! Setting up an Nginx reverse proxy with SSL termination is a great idea for enhancing security. I'll outline the steps for you:

1. **Install Nginx** (if you haven’t already):
   ```
   sudo apt update
   sudo apt install nginx
   ```

2. **Obtain your Let’s Encrypt SSL certificate** using Certbot. Assuming you're using Certbot:
   ```
   sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx
   sudo certbot --nginx -d yourdomain.com -d www.yourdomain.com
   ```
   Follow the prompts to complete the process.

3. **Update your Nginx configuration file** to set up the reverse proxy and enable SSL termination. You can edit your server block, typically located in `/etc/nginx/sites-available/default` or a configuration under `/etc/nginx/sites-available/`. Here’s an example configuration:
   ```
   server {
       listen 80;
       server_name yourdomain.com www.yourdomain.com;

       # Redirect all HTTP traffic to HTTPS
       return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
   }

   server {
       listen 443 ssl;
       server_name yourdomain.com www.yourdomain.com;

       # SSL certificate files
       ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem;
       ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem;

       # SSL settings
       ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
       ssl_prefer_server_ciphers on;
       ssl_ciphers HIGH:!aNULL:!MD5;

       # Reverse proxy settings
       location / {
           proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8080; # Adjust this to your backend app’s address/port
           proxy_http_version 1.1;
           proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
           proxy_set_header Connection 'upgrade';
           proxy_set_header Host $host;
           proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
       }
   }
   ```

4. **Test your configuration** to ensure it’s correct:
   ```
   sudo nginx -t
   ```
   If everything looks good, restart Nginx:
   ```
   sudo systemctl restart nginx
   ```

5. **Verify SSL** by navigating to your domain in a browser. You should see the lock icon, indicating SSL is working. You can also use tools like [SSL Labs](https://www.ssllabs.com/) to test your configuration for security.

