Absolutely! You can adapt the structure for displaying blog posts to showcase projects. Here’s a step-by-step guide and sample code snippets:

1. **Create a `projects` directory** in the `content` folder to store your MDX files for each project.

```bash
mkdir content/projects
```

Inside this folder, add individual MDX files for each project. For example:

```md
# content/projects/project1.mdx
---
title: "Project One"
description: "A detailed description of Project One."
date: "2023-10-15"
techStack: ["Next.js", "Tailwind CSS"]
---

This is the content of Project One.
```

2. **Create a TypeScript type for your project metadata** to improve type safety:

```tsx
// types/project.ts
export interface Project {
  title: string;
  description: string;
  date: string;
  techStack: string[];
}
```

3. **Modify your `getStaticProps` function** to read and parse MDX files from the `projects` directory:

```tsx
// lib/getProjects.ts
import fs from 'fs';
import path from 'path';
import matter from 'gray-matter';
import { Project } from '../types/project';

const projectsDirectory = path.join(process.cwd(), 'content/projects');

export function getProjects(): Project[] {
  const fileNames = fs.readdirSync(projectsDirectory);

  return fileNames.map((fileName) => {
    const filePath = path.join(projectsDirectory, fileName);
    const fileContents = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8');
    const { data } = matter(fileContents);

    return {
      title: data.title,
      description: data.description,
      date: data.date,
      techStack: data.techStack,
    };
  });
}
```

4. **Create a Projects page** that displays the projects dynamically:

```tsx
// pages/projects.tsx
import { GetStaticProps } from 'next';
import { Project } from '../types/project';
import { getProjects } from '../lib/getProjects';

interface ProjectsProps {
  projects: Project[];
}

const Projects: React.FC<ProjectsProps> = ({ projects }) => {
  return (
    <div className="p-4">
      <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">My Projects</h1>
      <ul className="space-y-4">
        {projects.map((project) => (
          <li key={project.title} className="border p-4 rounded-lg">
            <h2 className="text-2xl font-semibold">{project.title}</h2>
            <p>{project.description}</p>
            <p className="text-sm text-gray-500">{project.date}</p>
            <p className="text-sm font-medium">Technologies: {project.techStack.join(', ')}</p>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};

export const getStaticProps: GetStaticProps = async () => {
  const projects = getProjects();
  return { props: { projects } };
};

export default Projects;
```

5. **Style the projects page with Tailwind CSS** to make it visually appealing. For example, you can use utility classes for spacing, borders, and typography. You can customize it further to fit your design.

Let me know if you run into any issues or need help extending this functionality further!

Great question! To create individual pages for each project, we can use dynamic routing in Next.js. Here’s how you can set this up:

1. **Create a dynamic route in the `pages/projects/` directory:**

```bash
mkdir pages/projects
```
Then create a file named `[slug].tsx` inside the `pages/projects/` folder. This file will handle the dynamic routing based on the slug of each project MDX file.

2. **Update your `getProjects` function to include the slug:**

```tsx
// lib/getProjects.ts
export function getProjects(): Project[] {
  const fileNames = fs.readdirSync(projectsDirectory);

  return fileNames.map((fileName) => {
    const slug = fileName.replace(/\.mdx$/, '');
    const filePath = path.join(projectsDirectory, fileName);
    const fileContents = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8');
    const { data } = matter(fileContents);

    return {
      slug,
      title: data.title,
      description: data.description,
      date: data.date,
      techStack: data.techStack,
    };
  });
}
```

Now each project will have a `slug` property that corresponds to the file name.

3. **Implement the dynamic route and `getStaticPaths`:**

```tsx
// pages/projects/[slug].tsx
import { GetStaticPaths, GetStaticProps } from 'next';
import fs from 'fs';
import path from 'path';
import matter from 'gray-matter';
import { Project } from '../../types/project';

const projectsDirectory = path.join(process.cwd(), 'content/projects');

interface ProjectPageProps {
  project: Project;
}

const ProjectPage: React.FC<ProjectPageProps> = ({ project }) => {
  return (
    <div className="p-4">
      <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">{project.title}</h1>
      <p className="text-gray-600 mb-4">{project.description}</p>
      <p className="text-sm text-gray-500">{project.date}</p>
      <h2 className="text-xl font-semibold mt-6">Technologies Used:</h2>
      <ul className="list-disc ml-6">
        {project.techStack.map((tech) => (
          <li key={tech}>{tech}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};

export const getStaticPaths: GetStaticPaths = async () => {
  const fileNames = fs.readdirSync(projectsDirectory);
  const paths = fileNames.map((fileName) => ({
    params: { slug: fileName.replace(/\.mdx$/, '') },
  }));

  return { paths, fallback: false };
};

